section Mass Budget

    ~~~
    Breakdown of the rover's mass components. All values are notional
    estimates at the preliminary design review (PDR) level. Actual flight
    masses may vary by $\pm 15\%$ depending on structural margin
    requirements [@Wertz2011].
    ~~~

Chassis mass: m_c = 350 :kg

    ~ Primary structure and suspension frame. Sized for planetary terrain traversal.

Science payload mass: m_s = 120 :kg

    ~~~
    Notional instrument and harness breakdown:

    | Item                              | Mass (kg) |
    |-----------------------------------|-----------|
    | Imaging system                    |   8.0     |
    | Spectrometry suite                |   5.0     |
    | Subsurface radar                  |   6.2     |
    | Drill and sample cache            |  18.0     |
    | Environmental sensors             |   7.8     |
    | Electronics boxes                 |  40.0     |
    | Cabling and harness               |  22.0     |
    | Structural adapters and brackets  |  13.0     |
    | **Total**                         | **120.0** |
    ~~~

Power system mass: m_pw = 280 :kg

    ~~~
    Radioisotope thermoelectric generator (RTG). Electrical output is
    modelled in the Power section below.
    ~~~

Propulsion and mobility mass: m_mo = 250 :kg

    ~ Wheeled mobility system with independent drive and steering on each wheel.

Rover mass: m = m_c + m_s + m_pw + m_mo :kg

    ~~~
    Total rover mass. The mass budget is currently at $100\%$ of the
    allocated mass, with no margin. A contingency of $15\%$ should be
    added before the critical design review (CDR).
    ~~~

section Power

    ~~~
    Power is the primary mission constraint. The RTG output sets the
    duty cycle of all subsystems.
    ~~~

Beginning-of-mission power: P_0 = 110 :W

    ~ RTG electrical output at launch.

Plutonium-238 half-life: t_half = 87.7 :yr

Mission elapsed time: t = 14 :yr

$ Available power: P = P_0 * e ^ (-ln(2) * t / t_half) :W

    ~~~
    RTG output decays exponentially with the ${}^{238}Pu$ half-life:

    $$\lambda = \frac{\ln 2}{t_{1/2}}$$

    $$P = P_0 e^{-\lambda t} = P_0 e^{-\ln 2 \cdot t / t_{1/2}} \implies {{P:equation}}$$

    At $t = 14\,yr$, available output falls below the combined subsystem loads.
    ~~~

Science power: P_s = 45 :W
Mobility power: P_m = 40 :W
Housekeeping power: P_h = 25 :W

$ Power balance(-inf, inf): P_b = P - P_s - P_m - P_h :W

    ~ Positive value means feasible mission at the modeled mission time.
